docs.abstract: Amazon may be bigger than ever, but change is coming for the tech giants, too.
docs.snippet: Amazon may be bigger than ever, but change is coming for the tech giants, too.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Thursday, Amazon reported blockbuster first-quarter sales. This week Microsoft, Facebook and Google showed robust gains of their own. Supply chain disruptions and slowing ad revenue have put little dent in these cash-rich giants that, together with Apple, account for 20 percent of the S&P 500 index. Amid the biggest economic crisis since the Great Depression, Big Tech is roaring ahead.

headline.main: The Coronavirus Could Rewrite the Rules for Silicon Valley
headline.print_headline: Change Is Looming for Big Tech

docs.abstract: Harry Bosch, in Amazon’s Los Angeles cop procedural, and Doron Kavillio, in Netflix’s Israeli counterterrorism thriller, would have a lot to talk about if they weren’t so laconic.
docs.snippet: Harry Bosch, in Amazon’s Los Angeles cop procedural, and Doron Kavillio, in Netflix’s Israeli counterterrorism thriller, would have a lot to talk about if they weren’t so laconic.
docs.lead_paragraph: It’s April, so I must be writing about “Bosch.” This is the fifth straight year I’ve taken note of a new season (now the sixth) of Amazon Prime Video’s Los Angeles cop show based on Michael Connelly’s Harry Bosch novels. It’s an indulgence in a time when many worthwhile series go unremarked. This year, I can rationalize it as coronavirus-related: “Bosch” is my comfort show, the one I binge the day it’s available. On Friday I’ll be quarantined in my happy place.

headline.main: ‘Bosch’ and ‘Fauda’: The Platonic Ideal of the Tough Guy
headline.print_headline: Tough Guys, Strong, Silent and Lonely

docs.abstract: Recognized for the hit network sitcoms “The Office” and “Parks and Recreation,” Daniels is breaking his own conventions with a satirical sci-fi show on Amazon.
docs.snippet: Recognized for the hit network sitcoms “The Office” and “Parks and Recreation,” Daniels is breaking his own conventions with a satirical sci-fi show on Amazon.
docs.lead_paragraph: VANCOUVER, British Columbia — The new Amazon series “Upload” was in its final week of shooting last May, and Greg Daniels was chewing on everything he could get his hands on, including his hands. Time was waning, and the set — a convincing facsimile of a claustrophobic Queens apartment — was tricky to navigate. Daniels, the series’s creator, watched a monitor as the crew worked the tight spaces and the director shouted commands.

headline.main: With ‘Upload,’ Greg Daniels Takes a Leap Into the Great Unknown
headline.print_headline: For Greg Daniels, a Leap Into the Unknown
